data.sampled:
YES

Explanation: Let's represent the given information using set theory.

Let S be the set of all stars, L be the set of all luminous bodies, and B be the set of all bright objects.

The statement "All stars are luminous bodies" can be represented as S ⊆ L.
The statement "Some luminous bodies are bright" can be represented as ∃x ∈ L : x ∈ B.

Now, we want to show that "Some stars are bright." To do this, we can apply the logical operator ∃ (existential quantifier) to the premises, which corresponds to the "∃x" part in set notation.

We have S ⊆ L and ∃x ∈ L : x ∈ B. Using the set intersection (∩) and union (∪) operators, we can write this as (S ∩ L) ∪ B.

Now, we want to find the set (S ∩ L). Since every element in S is also an element in L, this is simply S. So, we have S ∪ B.

The union (∪) of two sets represents the elements that are in either set or both. In this case, we have found that some elements in S are also in B, meaning that some stars are bright.

Thus, the original statement is TRUE.
